	<li class="comment odd alt depth-4" id="comment-5762">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/34fe0e2717474b39fdceeb70302729fb?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/34fe0e2717474b39fdceeb70302729fb?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name">dante_hwd</span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2012-10-08T13:37:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2010/04/conditional-redirects-or-the-htaccess-malware.html#comment-5762">October 8, 2012</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Hi,<br />
I just cleaned out the third site with this issue.<br />
What is happening is that a file/page was injected into your site. This page gets called from the outside every x minutes (in my last case it was 15 minutes) and it will overwrite any .htaccess it can find.<br />
The only way out of this is to find the page first, remove it and then get rid of the affected .htaccess. Of course the challenge then is to identify how the page got in.<br />
Good luck</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
